\noindent\textit{We establish the \textbf{Aionometric Geometry}: a rigorous theory of logarithmic temporal representation built on the chronometric clock map $\tau = \lambda_\Delta \ln(t/t_0)$, where $\lambda_\Delta = 3722/2705$.  The clock constant is not a new fundamental constant but a prescribed coordinate parameter.  Its structural significance is revealed by the golden prime lattice: $\lambda_\Delta \equiv \vp^4 \pmod{229}$, placing it on the chromatic orbit $C_{57}$, with $229 - 217 = 12$ equaling the dodecahedral clock order.  The numerator carries Copper (primitive root, full-group access) and the denominator carries Bismuth (golden orbit, confinement).  The ratio is the clock that bridges full-group dynamics to golden confinement.}
\bigskip


% ════════════════════════════════════════════
\section{The Chronometric Clock Map}
\label{sec:chrono-clock}
% ════════════════════════════════════════════

The transformation from physical time $t$ to chronometric time $\tau$ is:
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:clock-map}
\tau = \lambda_\Delta \ln\!\left(\frac{t}{t_0}\right), \qquad \lambda_\Delta = \frac{3722}{2705} \approx 1.3760.
\end{equation}
This is a \emph{prescribed coordinate}, not a dynamical field.  No energy, momentum, stress-energy, or backreaction is assigned to $\tau$.  The following guardrails are enforced throughout:
\begin{itemize}[noitemsep]
\item $\delta S / \delta\tau$ is not introduced (no variational dynamics).
\item $p_\tau$ is not defined as a physical conjugate momentum.
\item $T_{\mu\nu}^{(\tau)}$ is not assigned.
\item $\lambda_\Delta$ is treated as a model parameter, not a new fundamental constant.
\end{itemize}

The operator calculus under $t \mapsto \tau$ transforms differential operators via:
\begin{align}
\partial_t &= \frac{\lambda_\Delta}{t}\,\partial_\tau, \\
\partial_t^2 &= \frac{\lambda_\Delta^2}{t^2}\!\left(\partial_\tau^2 - \lambda_\Delta^{-1}\,\partial_\tau\right), \\
\partial_t^n &= t^{-n}\,P_n(\partial_\tau;\,\lambda_\Delta),
\end{align}
where $P_n$ is an $n$-th degree polynomial whose coefficients are determined by Stirling numbers of the second kind $S(n,k)$.


% ════════════════════════════════════════════
\section{Golden Lattice Anchoring: $\lambda_\Delta = \vp^4$}
\label{sec:golden-anchor}
% ════════════════════════════════════════════

The clock constant decomposes as:
\begin{equation}
\lambda_\Delta = \frac{3722}{2705} = \frac{2 \times 1861}{5 \times 541}.
\end{equation}
Both 1861 and 541 are prime.  Their residues in $\FF_{229}^*$ reveal the structural anchoring:

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{clccl}
\toprule
Factor & Value & $\bmod 229$ & Element & Subgroup \\
\midrule
\multicolumn{5}{l}{\textit{Numerator: $3722 = 2 \times 1861$}} \\
$2$    & Helium  & $2$  & He & $C_{76}$ (third-order) \\
$1861$ & (prime) & $29$ & Cu & $C_{228}$ (\textbf{primitive root}) \\
\midrule
\multicolumn{5}{l}{\textit{Denominator: $2705 = 5 \times 541$}} \\
$5$    & Boron   & $5$  & B  & $C_{114}$ (half-order) \\
$541$  & (prime) & $83$ & Bi & $C_{57}$ (golden orbit) \\
\midrule
\multicolumn{5}{l}{\textit{Ratio}} \\
$\lambda_\Delta$ & $3722/2705$ & $\mathbf{217}$ & $\vp^4$ & $C_{57}$ (\textbf{chromatic}) \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\begin{theorem}[Golden Anchoring of $\lambda_\Delta$]
\label{thm:golden-anchor}
In $\FF_{229}^*$:
\begin{enumerate}[noitemsep]
\item $\lambda_\Delta \equiv \vp^4 \pmod{229}$, where $\vp^4 = 3\vp + 2$ (Fibonacci relation).
\item $\mathrm{ord}_{229}(\lambda_\Delta) = 57$: the clock sits on the chromatic orbit $C_{57}$.
\item $229 - 217 = 12$: the complement equals the dodecahedral clock order ($\mathrm{Ar}, \mathrm{Ac}$).
\item The numerator carries Cu ($\mathrm{ord} = 228$, full access); the denominator carries Bi ($\mathrm{ord} = 57$, confinement).  The clock is the \emph{ratio} of full-group dynamics to golden confinement.
\end{enumerate}
\end{theorem}

\noindent\textbf{Verification:} \texttt{python -m Principia} (chronometric module).


% ════════════════════════════════════════════
\section{Cross-Prime Profile}
\label{sec:cross-prime}
% ════════════════════════════════════════════

The clock constant evaluated across the golden prime lattice $\{229, 181, 139\}$:

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{cccccl}
\toprule
$p$ & Scale & $\lambda_\Delta \bmod p$ & $\vp^k$ & $\mathrm{ord}$ & Significance \\
\midrule
229 & Macro & 217 & $\vp^4$ & 57 & Chromatic orbit (golden anchor) \\
181 & Meso  & 26  & ---     & 12 & Dodecahedral subgroup \\
139 & Micro & 132 & ---     & 138 & Near-primitive ($= p - 1$) \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

At the macro prime $p = 229$, $\lambda_\Delta$ sits on the golden orbit.  At the meso prime $p = 181$, it drops to the dodecahedral subgroup --- the same order as the Ar-Ac clock.  At the micro prime $p = 139$, it is nearly a primitive root ($\mathrm{ord} = 138 = p - 1$), generating almost the full group.  This cross-prime behavior mirrors the epiperiodic structure: confinement at one scale, full access at another.


% ════════════════════════════════════════════
\section{Mellin--Chronometric Spectral Theory}
\label{sec:mellin}
% ════════════════════════════════════════════

Fourier modes in $\tau$ are Mellin modes in $t$:
\begin{equation}
\psi_\omega(t) = e^{i\omega\tau} = \left(\frac{t}{t_0}\right)^{i\omega\lambda_\Delta}.
\end{equation}
These are the standard Mellin modes, and the Mellin transform
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{M}[f](s) = \int_0^\infty t^{s-1} f(t)\,dt
\end{equation}
naturally diagonalizes scale transformations $t \mapsto Ct$, which become translations $\tau \mapsto \tau + \lambda_\Delta \ln C$ in chronometric time.

The golden orbit of $\FF_{229}^*$ has order 114, generating 114 discrete Mellin frequencies:
\begin{equation}
\omega_k = \frac{2\pi k}{114}, \qquad k = 0, 1, \ldots, 113.
\end{equation}
These are the \emph{natural spectral lines} of the chronometric theory at the macro scale.


% ════════════════════════════════════════════
\section{Multi-Clock Atlas and Adelic Clocks}
\label{sec:multi-clock}
% ════════════════════════════════════════════

Multiple prescribed clocks define an \textbf{affine clock atlas}:
\begin{equation}
\tau_a = \lambda_a \ln(t/t_{0a}), \qquad \tau_b = \lambda_b \ln(t/t_{0b}),
\end{equation}
with the transformation
\begin{equation}
\tau_b = \frac{\lambda_b}{\lambda_a}\,\tau_a + \lambda_b \ln(t_{0a}/t_{0b}).
\end{equation}
The three golden primes define three natural clocks with orbit lengths $(114, 45, 23)$ as their temporal scales.  Since $\gcd(114, 45, 23) = 1$, the superposition is \emph{epiperiodic}: quasiperiodic at every scale, exactly as a Penrose tiling is the projection of incommensurate lattice directions.

This is the \emph{temporal} manifestation of the Adelic Product Formula established in Chapter~\ref{ch:qc-tqc}: synthetic integration contracts the Lyapunov metric ($\varepsilon \to 0$) while expanding the $p$-adic metric ($\lambda \to \lambda + 1$).  Each $\Sigma$-consolidation step \emph{is} a chronometric tick of width $\lambda_\Delta$.

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{ccccl}
\toprule
Clock & $p$ & $\lambda$ & Orbit & Physical Scale \\
\midrule
Macro & 229 & $\lambda_\Delta$ & 114 & Geomagnetic, cosmological \\
Meso  & 181 & $\lambda_\Delta \cdot 45/114$ & 45 & Biological, solar cycle \\
Micro & 139 & $\lambda_\Delta \cdot 23/114$ & 23 & Atomic, quantum coherence \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}


